438","Keverell, St Martin, Cornwall, England":"St Martin by Looe, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Southampton, Hampshire, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Treadway","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>treden</i> ‘to tread, trample’ + <i>wei(e)</i> ‘way’, perhaps used for a vagrant or a well-traveled man."],"variants":[{"name":"Tredway","meanings":["English: variant of   Treadway  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Treadaway","meanings":["English: variant of   Treadway  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":55,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When William Treadway was born in 1400, in St Martin by Looe, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Treadway, was 25 and his mother, Martha Trugeon, was 20. He married Cecilia Speede in 1438, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 7 sons. He died in 1457, in Cornwall, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 57, and was buried in Cornwall, England."},"et":{"1400–1457":"1400–1457","1396–1460":"1396–1460","1422–1480":"1422–1480","1425–1480":"1425–1480","1425–1483":"1425–1483","1427–1480":"1427–1480","1430–1522":"1430–1522","1455–Male":"1455–Surnud","–1480":"–1480","1375–Male":"1375–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1396":"1396","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1380":"1380","1425":"1425","1457":"1457","1522":"1522","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1375":"1375","1427":"1427","1438":"1438","Keverell, St Martin, Cornwall, England":"St Martin by Looe, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Southampton, Hampshire, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, England"},"fi":{"1400–1457":"1400–1457","1396–1460":"1396–1460","1422–1480":"1422–1480","1425–1480":"1425–1480","1425–1483":"1425–1483","1427–1480":"1427–1480","1430–1522":"1430–1522","1455–Male":"1455–Kuollut","–1480":"–1480","1375–Male":"1375–Kuollut","1380–Female":"1380–Kuollut","1396":"1396","1483":"1483","1460":"1460","1480":"1480","1380":"1380","1425":"1425","1457":"1457","1522":"1522","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1455":"1455","1430":"1430","1375":"1375","1427":"1427","1438":"1438","Keverell, St Martin, Cornwall, England":"St Martin by Looe, Cornwall, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Southampton, Hampshire, England":"Southampton, Hampshire, England"},"fr":{"1400–1457":"1400–1457","1396–1460":"1396–1460","1422–1480":"1422–1480","1425–1480":"1425–1480","1425–1483":"1425–1483","1427–1480":"1427–1480","1430–1522":"1430–1522",